But a survey of the places where Keller's readings of the Odes and Epodes differ from those of other recent editors will show, I think, that his theory of the relation of the MSS. has not had any very revolutionary effect upon his text, that he admits con- jectures at least as largely as others, and that his conclusions, however they were formed, are supported generally by evidence from the Scholia or quotations‚ or by considerations of style, metre, and the like ¹.
